Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 475 degrees. Wash and dry
produce.

Dice @tomato{1}(diced). Core, deseed, and dice @long green pepper{1}(diced). Trim
and thinly slice @scallions{2}(thinly sliced). Quarter @lime{1}(quartered).

In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, scallions, a drizzle of @cooking oil{drizzle},
and juice from one lime wedge (two wedges for 4 servings). Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

In a separate small bowl, combine @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon} with lime juice to
taste. Add @water{1%tsp} at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.
Season with salt and pepper.

== Filling ==

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add green pepper,
salt, and pepper; cook until just softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Transfer to a third
small bowl.

Add another drizzle of oil to same pan. Add @ground beef{10%ounce}, half the
@Tex-Mex paste{1%unit}, half the @Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon} (you'll use
the rest of each later), salt, and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces,
until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it out.

Return green pepper to pan; stir to combine. Turn off heat.

== Enchiladas ==

Place a small amount of filling on one half of each @flour tortillas{6}. Roll up
tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create enchiladas. Place seam sides
down in an #8-by-8-inch baking dish{} (9-by-13-inch dish for 4 servings) or an
#ovenproof pan{}.

== Sauce ==

In a #medium bowl{}, combine @tomato paste{1%unit}, remaining Tex-Mex paste and
Southwest spice blend, and @water{1/2%cup} (3/4 cup for 4 servings).

Pour over enchiladas to thoroughly coat. Sprinkle with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}.

Bake on top rack until sauce is bubbly and cheese has melted, ~{3-5%minutes}.

== Serving ==

Top enchiladas with lime crema and pico de gallo. Divide between plates and serve
with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160º.